Abstract = {Syconia in successive developmental phases from Ficus lavigata Vahl (F.
   citrifolia Miller sensu DeWolf 1960) (Moraceae) and successive life
   stages of its fig wasp pollinator, Pegoscapus sp. (P. assuetus (Grandi)
   sensu Wiebes 1983) (Agaonidae) were dissected to elucidate their
   association with two undescribed species of nematodes.
   Parasitodiplogaster sp. (Diplogasteridae) are transported by female
   Pegoscapus sp, into the cavity of a phase B syconium as third-stage
   juveniles (J3), where they molt to the J4 stage and greatly increase in
   size in the hemocoel of the fig wasp after it begins to pollinate and
   oviposit in female florets. The J4 exit the wasp cadaver in a phase B or
   early phase C syconium, and molt to adults that mate and lay eggs. New
   J3 infect the next generation of female or male wasps as they emerge
   from their galls in phase D figs. Mated entomogenous females of
   Schistonchus sp. (Aphelenchoididae) are transported in the hemocoel of
   female wasps to the fig cavity of a phase B syconium. Female
   Schistonchus sp. exit the wasp and parasitize immature male florets
   causing an exudate, the development of hypertrophied epidermal cells of
   the anther filaments and anthers, and aberrations of the anther
   filament, anthers, and pollen. At least one generation of Schistonchus
   sp. occurs in the male florets. Entomogenous females appear at about the
   time that fig wasps molt to adults in their galls in late phase C
   syconia. Another Schistonchus sp. was recovered from females of P.
   mexicanus (Ashmead) (P. jimenezi (Grandi) sensu Wiebes 1983) and from
   the syconia of F. aurea Nuttall and appears to have a life cycle similar
   to that described for the Schistonchus sp. from F. laevigata.},
